# Basalt UI Framework – Wiki Training Data

Basalt is a modular UI library written in Lua for ComputerCraft (and similar environments). It is organized into several components and plugins that provide visual elements, an event system, rendering, and even program execution. This documentation describes the project’s architecture, key modules and files, as well as how to create and use elements.

---

## Overview of the Architecture

Basalt’s structure centers around these core pieces:

1. **Property System and Base Elements**  
   • The _propertySystem.lua_ file defines how objects have properties with getters, setters, and observers.  
   • Basic elements are defined in _BaseElement.lua_ which provides an event system and unique IDs.

2. **Visual Components**  
   • **VisualElement.lua** – Provides rendering methods (blit, text drawing, cursor support) and passes down calls to the parent (usually a frame).  
   • **Container.lua** – A subclass of VisualElement that can hold children elements. It handles event delegation for its children.

3. **Prebuilt UI Elements**  
Basalt ships with many reusable widgets such as:  
   • **Label.lua** – Displays text (with optional auto-sizing and wrapping).  
   • **Button.lua** – Can be clicked; supports centered text.  
   • **Input.lua** – A text entry component with support for cursor movement and a placeholder.  
   • **Checkbox.lua** – A toggle element with a custom “checked” mark.  
   • **Slider.lua** & **ProgressBar.lua** – Visual controls for showing or setting a value.  
   • **List.lua** and **Table.lua** – Lists items (with single or multi-selection) and tabular data with sorting support, respectively.  
   • **Dropdown.lua** – A combination of a label and list that drops down when activated.  
   • **BarChart.lua** – Displays numeric data using bars, while **Graph.lua** can render line charts.

4. **Advanced Elements**  
   • **Frame.lua** – A container that can be optionally draggable.  
   • **Display.lua** – A dedicated window element that wraps a native terminal window, allowing independent drawing.  
   • **Program.lua** – Allows running an external program inside a basalt frame, redirecting terminal output.

5. **Plugins**  
   • For example, _xml.lua_ shows how plugins can be defined. This one provides an XML parser that uses the property system and the Basalt error manager.

6. **Core Runtime (main.lua)**  
   • The _main.lua_ file ties everything together. It creates a “main frame” using BaseFrame and enters a loop that listens for events, forwards them to elements (or scheduled functions), and refreshes rendering.
   • It also provides APIs to create new elements via the element manager and to schedule tasks.

7. **Utility Libraries**  
   • _colorHex.lua_ – Maps colors to hexadecimal strings.  
   • _utils.lua_ – Provides helper functions such as text wrapping, deep copy, splitting strings, and UUID generation.  
   • _expect.lua_ – A function for verifying argument types and reporting errors using the error manager.

