## Advanced Topics

### Property and Events System

Every element uses the property system to define properties that automatically trigger rendering updates, type checks, and sometimes call setter functions. For example, in _VisualElement.lua_:  
- Properties like `x`, `y`, `width`, and `height` are defined using setters that call `updateRender()`.
- Events are registered (e.g., `mouse_click`, `key`, `char`) using helper methods in _BaseElement.lua_. When an element dispatches an event, it passes control (or focus) to its children or parent.

### Plugins

Plugins such as the _xml.lua_ demonstrate how you can extend Basalt. The XML plugin parses XML strings into tables that can then be used to configure elements. It uses the error manager (from _errorManager.lua_) to report parsing problems.

### Scheduling and Runtime

The runtime (in _main.lua_) includes a simple scheduler that queues and resumes coroutines. These scheduled functions are one way to run animations or deferred tasks.

